DOCUMENT();       

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
#           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
#           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
#           "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl",
#           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
"MathObjects.pl",
"AnswerFormatHelp.pl",
"PGcourse.pl",
           );
       
TEXT(beginproblem()); # standard preamble to each problem.

Context("Numeric");


$a = random(1,3,1);
$b = random(1,3,1);
$b_prod = $b*100;
$top = $a - $b*100;

$ans1 = Compute("$top/101");

BEGIN_TEXT

Find the exact solution to the equation below. ${BITALIC}(Do not give a decimal approximation.)${EITALIC}
$BR
$BR
\( \log_{10}($a  - x) - \log_{10}($b + x) = 2 \) 
$BR
$BR
\( x = \) \{ ans_rule(35) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("logarithms") \}

END_TEXT

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

ANS( $ans1->cmp(tolType=>'absolute',tolerance=>'0.0001') );

#ANS( num_cmp( $ans1,tol=>0.0001 ) );

$in1 = $a*101-$top;
$in2 = $b*101+$top;


SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 
Using \( \log{a}-\log{b} = \log{ \left( \frac{a}{b} \right)} \) we can rewrite the left side of the equation to read \( \log{ \left(\frac{$a-x}{$b+x}\right) } = 2 \) $BR $SPACE $BR

This logarithmic equation can be rewritten as \( 10^2 = \frac{$a-x}{$b+x} \ \) since if \( \log{a} = b \) then \( 10^b = a \).
$BR $SPACE $BR
Multiplying both sides of the equation by \( ($b+x) \) yields $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ 10^2($b+x) = $a-x \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ $b_prod + 100x = $a - x \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ 101 x = $a - $b_prod \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ x = \frac{$top}{101} \).
$BR $SPACE $BR
Check your answer: $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \log{ \bigg( $a - \left( \frac{$top}{101} \right) \bigg)} - \log{ \bigg( $b + \left( \frac{$top}{101} \right) \bigg)} = \log{ \left( \frac{$in1}{101} \right)} - \log{ \left( \frac{$in2}{101} \right) } \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ = \log{ \bigg( \left( \frac{$in1}{101} \right)/ \left( \frac{$in2}{101} \right) \bigg) } \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ = \log{ \left( \frac{$in1}{$in2} \right) } \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ = \log{100} = 2 \) $BR
which is what we want.
$BR
END_SOLUTION



